🌐 WebSocket Communication Patterns

🔑 Main Feature
The most important feature of WebSockets is:
✅ Continuous communication
✅ Two-way communication (bidirectional)

This means:
The client can send data to the server.
The server can also send data to the client.
Both can send messages anytime.
No interruption.
No need to refresh.

📈 Example: Stock Tracking App
Imagine a stock price app.

With HTTP:
You must refresh to see new prices.

With WebSockets:
The server keeps sending updated stock prices automatically.
You don’t need to request again.
Prices update in real time.

📡 Broadcasting (Very Important Concept)
WebSockets also allow something called:

📢 Broadcasting
Broadcasting means:
👉 The server sends the same message to many clients at the same time.

💬 Example: Chatroom Application

Let’s understand step by step:
One user sends a message to the server.
The server receives it.
The server sends that message to other connected users.
That is broadcasting.

🏠 Smaller Chat Rooms
Sometimes apps have different chat rooms.

In that case:
The server checks which room the sender is in.
It sends (broadcasts) the message only to users in that same room.
Not everyone gets the message.

So broadcasting can be:
To all users
Or to a selected group of users

📌 Three Communication Patterns in WebSockets
WebSockets support three main communication types:

1️⃣ Client ➝ Server

The client sends data to the server.
Example: Sending a chat message.

2️⃣ Server ➝ Client

The server sends data to one client.
Example: Sending updated stock price to one user.

3️⃣ Server ➝ Many Clients (Broadcasting)

The server sends the same data to many clients at once.
Example: Sending one user’s message to all other users in a chatroom.

🔥 Final Simple Summary

WebSockets allow:
Continuous connection
Two-way communication
Real-time updates
Broadcasting to multiple users

This makes them perfect for:
Chat apps
Live stock apps
Multiplayer games

Live notifications
